post_text: WAMS 7th Graders read and celebrated African American authors with culminating day today in the Media Center. After reading the books, the students wrote a book review and recommendation in Google Docs and then generated a QR code of their Google Doc. The QR codes were put on bookmarks they created. Bookmark tassels are color coded by genre and will be placed in the books. Using ipads, students and staff can scan the QR code and read the book recommendations to see if it piques their interest. SAMR in action!

A big thanks to everyone who attended the Community Engagement Forum: Funding the Future last week! Superintendent Dr. McCartney shared an update on what the district has been doing to help defray costs and increase revenues in this challenging financial climate and Amy Jablonski, from the Fair Funding Action Committee, gave an informative presentation on how state funding works, how it impacts Moorestown and what we can do to advocate for our schools and community. Please refer to the images below from the FFAC presentation, if you’d like to help advocate for fair funding for Moorestown.

We welcome your input and continued involvement --- please email Dr. McCartney at smccartney@mtps.com or the Board of Education (contact information at http://www.mtps.com/board_of_education/board_members) with any questions or suggestions.

The Moorestown Board of Education is pleased to announce that a contract agreement for the 2019-2022 school year has been reached with the Moorestown Education Association. REMINDER: The Board of Education Communications Committee will hold its third of a 3-Part Community Forum Series on tomorrow, May 14 at 6:30 PM in the William Allen Middle School Media Center. A discussion will take place about evolving our general approach with the World Class Learner conversation. This conversation involves more fully integrating social and emotional learning, the evolution of our curriculum to include more authentic problem solving and critical thinking opportunities, and strategic usage of technology. The goal will be a discussion around the strategies and solutions that we can support together to create a more student-centered learning environment that values and promotes the individual genius in each of our students

post_text:
On Monday, March 25, Moorestown Town Council and Mayor, Lisa Petriello, presented a proclamation to Moorestown High School's Vocational Transition Program and Job Developer Margie Bard in honor of Developmental Disabilities Awareness Month.

The program provides opportunities for students with special needs to learn job related skills through supported volunteer employment within the community. Many of our students work in local businesses and with the Township in various roles throughout the school year. Students also shared dog biscuits with Moorestown residents in attendance that were baked in our very own Bow Wow Bakery!

In addition, MHS students and staff supported World Down Syndrome Day by presenting a $230 donation to the Town Council. Funds were raised through purchases from "Common Grounds," our school’s new coffee cafe. The donation will assist the Moorestown Recreation Center’s programs for children with special needs.

Dear Moorestown Community,
Tomorrow evening, the Board of Education Communications Committee will hold its second Community Forum, Tuesday, March 26 at 6:30 PM in the William Allen Middle School Media Center. The second meeting will focus on how our students are dealing with the stress and anxiety they are feeling. From physical and mental health issues, to drug and alcohol usage, and other harmful effects and practices, we will have an open discussion so that we can work collectively on understanding and developing effective solutions for students.

Sincerely,

BOE Communications Committee

post_text:
Thanks to everyone who attended the Community Engagement Series Forum on Resilience last night! Over sixty people participated in a detailed, frank, and robust conversation about stress and resilience. Many perspectives were shared and the insight and candor from those present was appreciated and extremely useful to the conversation. The initial feedback we received was very positive regarding both the topic and the format.

We would love to have even more people at the next event on March 26th at 6:30 PM at WAMS where we will discuss risky behaviors in which our students have been engaging. Please watch this space for more details and plan to join us!

post_text: The Moorestown Township Board of Education Communications Committee invites you to attend a 3-part series on understanding and navigating the stresses of being a student in Moorestown. We know that many of our students, parents and staff share concerns about this issue and it is time to bring this critical conversation front and center. Please join us for our first community conversation on February 13, 2019 at 6:30 PM in the WAMS Media Center. For more specific information please visit our district webpage at www.mtps.com. Don’t miss this opportunity to be a part of the solution in helping our students to be happy, healthy and whole!
